SIMPLE: defiance
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Defiance
<hw>De*fi"ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>defiance</ets>, <ets>desfiance</ets>, challenge, fr.
<ets>desfier</ets> to challenge, F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧fier</ets>. See
<er>Defy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of defying, putting in
opposition, or provoking to combat; a challenge; a provocation; a
summons to combat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A war without a just <qex>defiance</qex> made.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stood for her cause, and flung <qex>defiance</qex> down.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A state of opposition; willingness to flight;
disposition to resist; contempt of opposition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He breathed <qex>defiance</qex> to my ears.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A casting aside; renunciation; rejection.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Defiance</xex> to thy kindness.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Ford.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To bid defiance</b></col>, <col><b>To set at
defiance</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to defy; to disregard recklessly or
contemptuously.</cd> <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Defiant</ent>⟦br⟧
